pades, and the British government, upon discovering the diaries, circulated its pages to public figures, thereby crippling what had been a mounting petition for clemency. In 1916, he was hanged. In this gripping reimagining, acclaimed historian Martin Duberman paints a full portrait of the man for the first time. Tracing his evolution from servant of the empire to his work as a humanitarian activist and anti-imperialist, Duberman resurrects and recognizes all facets—from the professional to the personal—of the fantastic life of this pioneer for human rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAutonomy and independence movements. 0aFICTION / Historical. 0aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century. 0aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century. 0aHuman rights workersvFiction. 0aHuman rights workersxFiction. 0aHuman rights workers. 0aIndians of South AmericaxFictionxHistoryxAmazon River Valley. 0aIndians of South AmericazAmazon River ValleyxHistoryvFiction. 0aIndians of South America. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  a1911.  a1916.  a20th century.  aanti imperialist.  aarmed rebellion.  abritish government.  abritish rule.  abrutal conditions.  acongo.  aconvicted of treason.  adeath sentence.  adetailed diaries.  aenslaved labor.  agay man.  ageorge bernard shaw.  agerman support.  ahumanitarian activist.  aindigenous people.  airish nationalist.  aking leopold.  aknighted.  aperu.  apetition for clemency.  aservant of the empire.  asexual escapades.  atrial.  awidespread atrocities.  aworld war 1.  aworldwide attention.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029888040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052097085440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97805209708